World Doula Week… and I have so many thoughts to share. 

I didn’t start my journey of becoming a doula as a “career” and as far as I’m concerned, it still isn’t - it’s something so much deeper and meaningful to me… Something that lives in me, something I breathe, alongside many other women who feel that same pull to this beautiful line of work. A true calling, if you will. 

The long nights, greeted by the early morning sunrise… the hot cups of coffee brought to you by giddy and exhausted new dads at 4am… The way you can look at your laboring mama, and know right where she’s at… holding her, supporting her, witnessing her strength… man, you feel it all to your core, at least I do. 

There’s the hard ones too… the one’s that don’t end how you feel they should… that you internally battle with while you fall asleep at night with tear filled eyes, just wishing you could take it and carry the weight.

Being a doula is holy and sacred work and being welcomed into a birth space is something I’ll never tire of or take for granted. I wouldn’t trade the middle of the night texts, the 3am leap out of bed and race to a birth rush, the sore joints and the tired eyes.

I started doing this because women need each other more than ever during this massive moment in their lives. We need to see each other birthed into mothers again and again. Something shifts… it’s powerful and it never ever gets old.

I think I go back and forth on what to post in this space about what I do - because at times it can feel so sacred that I can’t possibly do it justice in a little caption.

What I can tell you is that time and time again, I hold my sweet mamas while their body moves baby down, and I feel it with her. We ride that wave together, I remind her not to tense, but also remind her that I know how it feels to be tense. I watch as she’s birthed while she births her baby - 1st or 5th it’s all the same. A new mama. I hold my breath while she pushes, and tear up as baby is pulled to her chest.

Sometimes I drive home from the hard ones with hot tears in my eyes wishing I could have taken her place, and smile at the photos I have of their sweet new family. joy and pain, highs and lows swirled into one day. 

I just really really love being a doula.

There’s a message going around that birth looks a certain way through this tiny tiny lens of IG.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
As a birth worker its hard for me to explain to my clients while you see beautiful video and photos - what you miss is the grit, the vocalizing, the tears, and yes the raw pain or intensity of it. It’s beautiful, and holy. It is what makes it so transformative on the other side. If it was “pain free” the after just wouldn’t the same. If you screamed, or moaned, or cussed, or didn’t have a aesthetic birth tub or a hospital birth it does NOT mean you should feel shame. The exact opposite is true, you are strong mama 💥
